nd since  is taking a lesson from the us behemoth to survive as a standalone firmbaillie gifford  co which oversees about us billion  billion out of edinburgh has been cutting fees to remain competitive in a lowreturn environment a strategy that takes a page from vanguards while peers such as crosstown rival standard life investments are turning to mergers and acquisitions to weather the assault from index funds this firm is betting that performance is still key to attracting clients including vanguard for which it oversees more than us billionweve learned quite a lot from vanguard said charles plowden joint senior partner at baillie gifford whos been with the asset manager for more than three decades cutting fees is one part of our defense of active management were not going to be able to beat them on costs and we are not going to try but its about performance after costs related quotes  years  day last updated updating last updated updating view full quote company profile asx announcements expand asx announcements view all announcements plowden together with two other baillie gifford fund managers runs about a third of the us billion vanguard global equity fund which invests in stocks including some of worlds largest technology companies the fund is beating  per cent of peers over the past five years its expense ratio  the total cost of managing a fund  was  per cent below the average of similar money pools as of january according to vanguardthat success is also a model for baillie gifford the firm has cut overall fees on some funds and introduced a twotiered system on others that lowers charges above a certain threshold for assets under management for the scottish mortgage investment trust the fee falls to  basis points from  basis points for assets above  billion pounds  billionamong their bond funds fees range from  to  basis points and for multiasset products the company charges between  and  basis points according to data provided by the companyspurring imita